x-kaytu-explanation:
In Azure, data in Storage Accounts are encrypted by default at the service and infrastructure level using Storage Service Encryption (SSE). However, Azure also offers an additional layer of encryption to secure your data at the hardware-level using Azure Disk Encryption. This is what is referred to as "double encryption".

Here's how you can enable it in Azure Resource Manager (ARM) template (a form of Azure Markup):

```json
"resources": [
    {
      "name": "[parameters('storageAccountName')]",
      "type": "Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts",
      "apiVersion": "2019-06-01",
      "location": "[parameters('location')]",
      "kind": "StorageV2",
      "sku": {
        "name": "Standard_RAGRS",
        "tier": "Standard"
    },
    "properties": {
        "encryption": {
            "services": {
                "blob": {
                    "enabled": true,
                    "defaultServiceVersion": "2019-06-01"
                },
                "file": {
                    "enabled": true
                }
            },
            "keySource": "Microsoft.Storage",
            "requireInfrastructureEncryption": true
        }
    }
}
]
```

In this ARM template:

- `Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts` specifies the type of resources to create; in this case, Storage Accounts.
- The `encryption` property inside `properties` is where you specify the encryption settings.
  - `services` specify which services to encrypt (Blob service and File service)
  - `keySource` specifies that encryption keys will be managed by Azure storage.
  - `requireInfrastructureEncryption` when set to `true`, enables double encryption.

Please note that double encryption can generate additional data ingress and egress costs and slightly higher latencies.
